ting that is far removed from the geographical boundaries of the Western world. In that connection, this volume is partly intended to serve as an antidote to much of the Western commentary on Asia-Pacific security issues by providing a range of perspectives on those issues from the Southeast Asian point of view. It offers a range of Southeast Asian perspectives on the multifaceted security issues that confront the Asia-Pacific region in the post-Cold War era. That there is no unitary perspective emanating from the region is symptomatic of the very fluid geopolitical situation that characterizes Asia-Pacific security, and, of equal import, the different schools of thought that analysts in the region have chosen to subscribe to.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aNational securityzSoutheast Asia. 0aNational security--Southeast Asia. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh1 aAnwar, Dewi Fortuna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCastro, Renato Cruz De, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCunha, Derek da, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEr, Lam Peng, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHassan, Mohamed Jawhar bin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNum, Mak Joon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSebastian, Leonard C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSingh, Daljit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWah, Chin Kin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 ada Cunha, Derek, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (20